This paper deals with game theory and computational complexity, which are both central topics in computer science. The focus on hedonic games and the use of algorithms to find stable outcomes suggest that cs.GT (Game Theory and Economics) is the most likely sub-category. The use of polynomial time algorithms and the empirical analysis suggest that cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) and cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) are also likely sub-categories. The consideration of multiple classes and the use of better-response dynamics suggest that cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) may also be a relevant sub-category. Finally, the use of computational complexity results suggests that cs.LG (Machine Learning) may be a less likely but still possible sub-category.
